                "name": "Francisco Ojeda",
                "href": "/profile/Francisco-Ojeda-12"
            },
            "answer_text": "The correct answer is \u2018yes\u2019. Yet it really depends on what you mean \u2018fact checked\u2019. If it a non-fiction, it is imperative for the reputation of the author for the facts to be accurate. For a fictional work, facts can be interpreted as long as they are not referenced from someone or somewhere else. One cannot say that a real person said something unless the story references the statement. Examples: (1) A fictional account of Benjamin Franklin traveling to the present would not need to validate what he happens to say. (2) A fictional yet detailed account of a winter in Montana does not to be accurate for the time period. ",
